Requirements (this is just a summary; see instructions below) Style a form that
includes various fields (text inputs, radio buttons, checkboxes). Use the:focus
pseudoclass to change the border and background color of input fields when they
are focused. Utilize the :checked pseudoclass to style radio buttons and
checkboxes differently when they are selected. Apply the :invalid and :valid
pseudoclasses to provide visual feedback on input validation. For example,
outline text inputs in green (:valid) or red (:invalid) depending on their
content validity according to their required attribute. Create an ordered or
unordered list of items (e.g., a list of books, articles, or any topic of
interest). Use the :first-child and :last-child pseudoclasses to style the first
and last items of the list distinctly. Implement the :nth-child pseudoclass to
style even and odd items differently for a zebra-striping effect. Optionally,
use the :not() pseudoclass to exclude certain items from being styled by other
rules, adding complexity and variety to your styling. Instructions: HTML Setup:
Use the provided HTML (see below), or create a basic HTML structure with a
element containing various types of inputs and a ul or ol list with at least 10
items. CSS Styling: Write CSS rules targeting the form inputs using :focus,
:checked, :invalid, and :valid pseudoclasses. Style the list using :first-child,
:last-child, :nth-child, and optionally :not() pseudoclasses for advanced
styling. Validation and Feedback: Ensure that form inputs have appropriate type
attributes and required attributes where necessary to make use of the :invalid
and :valid pseudoclasses effectively. Deliverable: Submit the HTML and CSS
files. The web page should visually distinguish form inputs based on their state
(focus, checked, validity) and create a visually appealing list that
demonstrates mastery of structural pseudoclasses.

<!-- <!DOCTYPE html>
